hared and contested. This book brings together, through 13 interviews and biographies, the lives, experiences and contributions of leading social work educators from Comoros, the Caribbean, India, Mexico, Sweden, Switzerland, the United States and the United Kingdom. Their receipt of IASSW’s Katherine Kendall Award recognized that they were at the forefront of establishing and securing social work education during this period of internationalization. Exploring the aims and priorities of these leading social work educators, Askeland and Payne draw out a historical and contextual account of how social work education became widely adopted in different national and cultural environments. The Awardees’ diverse lives and professional experiences reveal the issues they faced, the paths they travelled and the prospects and threats confronting social work and its education more widely.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aSocial work educationvCross-cultural studies. 0aSocial work educationxAwards. 0aSocial work education. 70(DE-601)10583582X0(DE-588)4112628-2aAusbildung2gnd 70(DE-601)1061571590(DE-588)4055676-1aSozialarbeit2gnd 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Work.2bisacsh1 aAronsson, Pia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAskeland, Gurid Aga, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBediako, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHealy, Lynne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKendall, Katherine A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLittlechild, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNadkarni, Vimla V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPayne, Malcolm, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov